<TITLE> Milk Vita pastures grabbed by locals </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 Dhaka, April 11 (bdnews24.com)Influential people have grabbed about 80 percent of the pastures around the Milk Vita complex in Baghabarighat, Sirajganj, a parliamentary probe has found out. The probe body feared that if the government did not recover the encroached land immediately, the cattle raisers were surely to face fodder crisis due to a decline in production of milk and milk products. The parliamentary standing committee on local government and cooperatives ministry formed the three-member probe body headed by Awami League MP Ali Ashraf Khan Khasru. The committee in its meeting Sunday accepted the probe report and suggested that the government take measures to resolve problems of Bangladesh Milk Producers' Cooperative Union, popularly known as Milk Vita. "The standing committee has brought the problem to the government. It is up to the government to take measures to protect the pasture grounds," Rahmat Ali, the standing committee chairman, told bdnews24.com Sunday after the meeting. He said the government must go for action to recover the land. "The state minister (Jahangir Kabir Nanak) just told us he would look into it," said Ali. The report states that grazing field in the Baghabari area came decreased to just 1,000 acres from a previous 5,000. "Influential people have been eating up the grazing fields," said the report. "The government should immediately lease the existing 1031 acres of land to the Bangladesh Milk Producers' Cooperative Union Ltd. Rahmat Ali said, "If the pastures are not protected now, farmers will face fodder crisis hampering production of dairy products." The ministry sources say that Milk Vita produces over 3 million litres of milk per year
